{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659525","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659525"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:09:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:09:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20864"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20864"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13739"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97373"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13739"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20864"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79988"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"11595"},{"type":"tags","id":"12372"},{"type":"tags","id":"12685"},{"type":"tags","id":"12686"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33066"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33067"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97373"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECentral tolerance mechanisms prevent autoimmunity by eliminating self-reactive lymphocytes during their development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a mechanism of central tolerance?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Phagocytosis of self-reactive B cells by macrophages","Activation of regulatory T cells in peripheral tissues","Apoptosis of self-reactive T cells in the thymus","Cytokine inhibition of lymphocyte proliferation","Antibody-mediated neutralisation of self-antigens"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Eapoptosis of self-reactive T cells in the thymus\u003C/strong\u003E. This process, known as negative selection or clonal deletion, is a key mechanism of central tolerance. When developing T cells in the thymus express T cell receptors (TCRs) that strongly recognise self-antigens presented by thymic antigen-presenting cells, they receive signals that trigger apoptosis, eliminating potentially autoreactive cells before they can mature and enter circulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivation of regulatory T cells in peripheral tissues\u003C/strong\u003E - While some regulatory T cells do develop in the thymus as part of central tolerance, their activation in peripheral tissues is a mechanism of peripheral tolerance, not central tolerance.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntibody-mediated neutralisation of self-antigens\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not a mechanism of tolerance; rather, it would represent an autoimmune response.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECytokine inhibition of lymphocyte proliferation\u003C/strong\u003E - While cytokines can regulate immune responses, this describes a peripheral regulatory mechanism, not central tolerance.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhagocytosis of self-reactive B cells by macrophages\u003C/strong\u003E - Self-reactive B cells in the bone marrow typically undergo receptor editing (changing their antigen specificity) or apoptosis, not phagocytosis by macrophages.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECentral tolerance is critical for preventing autoimmunity. In the thymus, the AIRE (autoimmune regulator) protein enables expression of tissue-restricted antigens, allowing for deletion of T cells that might react against these self-antigens. Similarly, in the bone marrow, B cells that strongly recognise self-antigens undergo receptor editing or apoptosis. However, central tolerance is not perfect, and self-reactive lymphocytes that escape these mechanisms require additional peripheral tolerance mechanisms to prevent autoimmune disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Central tolerance is the process by which self-reactive T and B lymphocytes are eliminated or inactivated during their development in primary lymphoid organs.","Negative selection in the thymus eliminates self-reactive T cells through apoptosis when they recognise self-antigens.","The AIRE protein enables expression of tissue-restricted antigens in the thymus, facilitating deletion of T cells reactive to these antigens.","B cells that recognise self-antigens in bone marrow undergo receptor editing or apoptosis to prevent autoimmunity."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 6; pages 216-217."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79988"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20864"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79988","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79988"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-06T13:10:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-06T13:19:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13739"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97373"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4936","links":